'The tidyverse is an opinionated collection of R packages designed for data science.' It's another set of tools. Some of them are alternatives to the base #rstats library that aim to be more consistent, more useful or faster. Some of them are entirely new!

Statically typed languages (like Scala) check var type at compile time, so once decided type is static (unchanging). Dynamically typed languages (like #rstats , #pydata ) check type at run time so vars can change type as they change values. https:// stackoverflow.com/questions/1517 582/what-is-the-difference-between-statically-typed-and-dynamically-typed-languages … #DSLearnings pic.twitter.com/8UepeTRmp6

#rstats #purrr Compute quantiles/percentiles: library(dplyr); library(magrittr); library(purrr) mtcars %>% select(.,mpg, wt) %>% map(., quantile, probs = c(0.10, 0.90), na.rm=TRUE) %>% http:// as.data .frame(.) %>% `rownames<-`(c("10%", "90%"))
